Step 1: First, go to the preprocessing folder located in the codes folder. Navigate to the `main.m` file.

Step 2: Modify the directories for your input RGB images that require preprocessing, such as color fusion and enhancement.

Step 3: Save the enhanced images in the output directory specified in `main.m`.

Step 4: Store the outputs as required for the USOD code, as illustrated below.![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Step 5: Below are the RGB directories for test and train datasets, respectively.![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Step 6: Navigate to the directory containing `train\_test\_eval.py`. Open it and update the paths to your stored pretrained model, trainset, testset, and other required files.![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Step 7: Once all directories and requirements for training, testing, and evaluation are set up, run the following command: 

python3 train\_test\_eval.py --Training 1 --Testing 1 --Evaluation 1 > log/loss.log &

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Step 8: Afterward, you will observe epochs running, as shown below.

Step 9: To check the last 300 lines of the log, use the following command:

tail -f -n 300 log/loss.log

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Step 10: After 200 epochs, the testing procedure begins, as seen below.

Step 11: At the 60,000th iteration, a checkpoint will be saved as `UVST.pth`.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Step 12: Evaluation metrics will be available in `result.txt`. Below are attached results for the model.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Step 13: In the zip file `30\_dl\_code`, I have included preprocessing and `USOD\_10k` code. Preprocessing comprises color enhancement Matlab code, while `USOD\_10k` contains datasets, pretrained models, and Python files for evaluation, testing, and training.![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
